title: Building on Raspberry Pi 4B with OpenVINO provider does not link correctly
body:
**Description**
Compiling onnxruntime from source on ARMv7l (Raspberry Pi OS) with the openvino provider fails, because ld cannot find the openvino libraries.
`/usr/bin/ld: cannot find -linference_engine`
`/usr/bin/ld: cannot find -linference_engine_legacy`
I believe the error is in `cmake/onnxruntime_providers.cmake` line 624. https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/a046ef133aa18bda7b7ec9eeedfec4800f452d45/cmake/onnxruntime_providers.cmake#L621-L625
CMake checks to use either the directory "aarch64" or "intel64", but not "armv7l" where the libraries are actually installed. Changing this line seems to fix the issue and the build completes.


**System information**
- Raspberry Pi 4B with Rasberry Pi OS Lite (2020-12-02)
- ONNX Runtime installed from github source.
- ONNX Runtime version: latest master branch (commit a046ef133aa18bda7b7ec9eeedfec4800f452d45)
- Python version: 2.7.16 and 3.7.3
- GCC version: gcc (Raspbian 8.3.0-6+rpi1) 8.3.0
- OpenVINO version: 2021.1

**To Reproduce**
These commands are run directly on the Raspberry Pi (via ssh because it's headless):
```
# opencv and tbb should be installed
# install openvino (according to intel docs)
mkdir -p Downloads && cd Downloads
wget https://download.01.org/opencv/2021/openvinotoolkit/2021.1/l_openvino_toolkit_runtime_raspbian_p_2021.1.110.tgz
sudo mkdir -p /opt/intel/openvino
sudo tar -xf  l_openvino_toolkit_runtime_raspbian_p_2021.1.110.tgz --strip 1 -C /opt/intel/openvino
sudo apt update && sudo apt install -y cmake
source /opt/intel/openvino/bin/setupvars.sh
echo "source /opt/intel/openvino/bin/setupvars.sh" >> ~/.bashrc
sudo usermod -a -G users "$(whoami)"
sh /opt/intel/openvino/install_dependencies/install_NCS_udev_rules.sh

# reboot or logout in order for group changes to take effect

# install onnxruntime
cd ~
git clone --recursive https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime.git
cd onnxruntime
./build.sh --update --build --build_shared_lib --arm --config Release --use_openmp --use_openvino MYRIAD_FP16 --parallel
```

title: Fix AMD multi-tensor implementation.
body:
**Description**:
ROCM appears to have an issue with the Lamb reduction kernel when launched with >256 threads per block (the results are severely incorrect and non-deterministic).  The current multi_tensor code will launch up to 512 threads per block.  Launching the same code with 256 threads per block produces the expected results.

The change here is to duplicate the CUDA multi_tensor header into a ROCM-specific version, and cap the threads at 256.

title: save data to and load data from an hdf5 file for checkpointing
body:
**Description**: Implementation of internal utility functions for saving to and loading from hdf5 file. These functions are useful for ```ORTTrainer``` checkpointing functionality.

**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?
These changes are required to save and load an ```ORTTrainer``` checkpoint to and from an hdf5 file. 
  - More details on why hdf5 file format is required for ```ORTTrainer``` checkpointing:

    The main reason for a special file format is related to distributed training. In a distributed training scenario, each worker (or process) would write its own states to an output file. It is important to map each checkpoint file to its original rank along with the distributed environment training configuration, such as world size and type of distributed training. The existing checkpoint design embeds such information on filenames (e.g. common prefix along with world_rank, workd_size and other such parameters (encoded as strings) on the file name). This is necessary in order to correctly identify the rank of the file being loaded so it can be loaded into the corresponding trainer or to aggregate all checkpoints in proper order. But naming the files as such has certain drawbacks:
    - File names cannot be changed, affecting future extensions and BC concerns.
    - All checkpoint files need to reside in the same folder.
    - Since there is a default prefix name is hardcoded in the API, the file can be easily mistakenly overwritten.
    - Rank, world size and other ZeRO information is embedded in the file name.

    The proposal is to embed relevant metadata inside the file, which could have any friendly name as per the users liking. While loading, each file is partially read to build a map. Using pickle is avoided because it would require loading the entire checkpoint file (which could be huge) and discarding it in case it does not align with the one we are looking for. Here is where hdf5 comes into play. Hdf5 file format allows us to read only a part of the file (relevant metadata). This should enable us to build the rank to file name map fast and easily.

Implement ScatterND ops in CUDA.
